1. Open `vscode/build/gulpfile.vscode.js` in Code
2. Run Format (or simply save the file, in case you have auto format on save)

The file changes considerably, and forbids me to use a more compact formatting, like it used to. Some examples:

```es6
const builtInExtensions = [
	{ name: 'ms-vscode.node-debug', version: '1.15.2' },
	{ name: 'ms-vscode.node-debug2', version: '1.14.4' }
];
```

becomes

```es6
const builtInExtensions = [
  {
    name: 'ms-vscode.node-debug',
    version: '1.15.2'
  },
  {
    name: 'ms-vscode.node-debug2',
    version: '1.14.4'
  }
];
```

or

```es6
	const localExtensionDependencies = gulp.src('extensions/node_modules/**', { base: '.' });
```

becomes

```es6
    const localExtensionDependencies = gulp.src('extensions/node_modules/**', {
      base: '.'
    });
```

I am forced to disable auto format on save for javascript files. ðŸ˜¢

I had this test in my extension which began failing with the 1.14 release:

```ts
const ext = vs.extensions.getExtension("DanTup.dart-code");

it("is not activated initially", () => {
  assert.equal(ext.isActive, false);
});
it("is activated successfully upon opening a Dart file", done => {
  vs.workspace.openTextDocument(sampleFileUri)
    .then(() => assert.equal(ext.isActive, true)) // This fails with false !== true
    .then(() => assert.notEqual(extension.sdks.dart, null))
    .then(() => assert.notEqual(extension.analyzer, null))
    .then(() => done(), e => done(new Error(e)));
  });
```

The extension works fine so I don't think there are no real consequences of this but before I change the test I wanted to make sure this was an expected change (I tried looking through source of getExtension/openTextDocument but couldn't see any obvious change). My guess is that some either timing changed in openTextDocument such that it returns earlier (before related extensions are activated) or the result from `getExtension` isn't "live" anymore and won't automatically return an updated value?
